# Git — Feature branch tracking

**Never** let a feature/fix/hotfix branch track `origin/main`. A plain `git push` updates whatever upstream is set — if upstream is `main`, you push directly to production’s default branch and skip the PR workflow.

## Create a feature branch

```bash
git fetch origin main
git checkout -b feature/my-feature origin/main
```

Use prefixes: `feature/`, `fix/`, `hotfix/` (match existing repo style).

## First push — set upstream to the same branch name

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
# or explicitly:
git push -u origin feature/my-feature
```

After this, `git branch -vv` must show:

```text
feature/my-feature  abc1234 [origin/feature/my-feature] ...
```

**Not:**

```text
feature/my-feature  abc1234 [origin/main] ...
```

## Before pushing — verify tracking

```bash
git branch -vv
git status -sb
```

If upstream is `origin/main` on a non-`main` branch:

```bash
git branch --unset-upstream
git push -u origin HEAD
```

## Open a PR (required for feature work)

`git push` does **not** open a PR. After the branch exists on GitHub:

```bash
gh pr create --base main --head feature/my-feature \
  --title "..." \
  --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
- ...

## Test plan
- [ ] ...
EOF
)"
```

## Agent checklist

When starting feature work:

1. Create or checkout a named branch (not `main`).
2. Confirm upstream is **not** `origin/main`.
3. First push uses `git push -u origin HEAD`.
4. Offer `gh pr create` when the user wants to share or merge — never push feature commits to `main` unless explicitly asked.

## Commits

Only commit when the user asks. Never `git push` to `main` for feature work unless the user explicitly requests it.
